 violently with the army in the streets of Bangkok. Conflict between groups for and against former Prime Minister Thaksin has polarized Thai society. Under his watch, violence also returned to the Malay Muslim south, with the loss of over 3,000 lives. The military coup that ousted Thaksin was supposed to end all this, but instead polarization increased and southern violence continued. This book is about how Thaksin divided Thailand, the nature of the southern conflict, and problematic attempts to establish a consensus around a post-Thaksin political order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / General.2bisacsh1 aArya, Gothom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBunbongkarn, Suchit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharoensin-o-larn, Chairat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnors, Michael K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFunston, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFunston, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLiow, Joseph Chinyong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontesano, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuntarbhorn, Vitit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNidhiprabha, Bhanupong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPongsudhirak, Thitinan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobinson, Glen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSatha-Anand, Chaiwat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWarr, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g